"Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Ballenstein","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: perhaps a habitational name from a minor or lost place so named, derived from <i>galle</i> ‘wet, damaged spot (in a field)’ +   Stein  . This surname is rare in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Stein","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>stein</i>, German <i>Stein</i> ‘rock’, hence a topographic name either for someone who lived on stony ground or for someone who lived by a notable outcrop of rock or by a stone boundary marker or monument. It could also be a metonymic occupational name for a mason or stonecutter, or, among Jews, an artificial name. This surname is also found elsewhere in central Europe, e.g. in Czechia, where it is also spelled <b>Štein</b>, and in Poland.","Dutch: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Augustijn</i> (see   Austin  ) or a habitational name from any of the Dutch places called Stein.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of ten or more farmsteads, notably in southeastern Norway, from Old Norse <i>steinn</i> ‘stone’, most often named from a big rock on the farm."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Herzogin von Kärnten Mathilde von Ballenstein was born about 1005, in Austria. She had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Konrad von Kärnten II, Herzog."},"et":{"um 1005–":"umbes 1005–Surnud","1003–1039":"1003–1039","1020–1061":"1020–1061","1026–1070":"1026–1070","1028–Male":"1028–Surnud","1005–Female":"1005–Surnud","1028":"1028","1039":"1039","1005":"1005","1026":"1026","1003":"1003","um 1026":"umbes 1026","1020":"1020","about 1020":"umbes 1020","1061":"1061","um 1005":"umbes 1005","1070":"1070","Stuttgart, Württemberg, Deutschland":"Oberamt Stuttgart, Württemberg, Saksamaa","Österreich":"Austria","Schwaben,Bavaria":"Schwaben, Bayern, Saksamaa","Hzgt. Kamten HRR":"Heiliges Römisches Reich"},"fi":{"um 1005–":"noin 1005–Kuollut","1003–1039":"1003–1039","1020–1061":"1020–1061","1026–1070":"1026–1070","1028–Male":"1028–Kuollut","1005–Female":"1005–Kuollut","1028":"1028","1039":"1039","1005":"1005","1026":"1026","1003":"1003","um 1026":"noin 1026","1020":"1020","about 1020":"noin 1020","1061":"1061","um 1005":"noin 1005","1070":"1070","Stuttgart, Württemberg, Deutschland":"Oberamt Stuttgart, Württemberg, Saksa","Österreich":"Itävalta","Schwaben,Bavaria":"Schwaben, Bayern, Saksa","Hzgt. Kamten HRR":"Heiliges Römisches Reich"},"fr":{"um 1005–":"environ 1005–Décédée","1003–1039":"1003–1039","1020